1️⃣ What is render_template() ?
Definition
render_template() is used to send an HTML file from the templates folder to the browser.
......................
Meaning:
Python (app.py)
        ↓
render_template()
        ↓
HTML file
        ↓
Browser shows webpage
.......................
Example:
return render_template("home.html")
Flask will look for:
templates/home.html
..............................
2️⃣ Flask Project Structure
Flask requires a templates folder.
Flask_Project
│
├── app.py
│
└── templates
      │
      └── home.html
Important rule:
HTML files must be inside templates folder

..........................................
3️⃣ app.py (Backend Code)
Example Flask code:

from flask import Flask, render_template

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route("/")
def home():
    return render_template("home.html")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(debug=True)
............................
Explanation:
Flask--	create Flask app
render_template	--load HTML file
"home.html"	---file inside templates folder
..........................
4️⃣ templates/home.html (Frontend)
